00:15:43.390 --> 00:15:48.150
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:51.490 --> 00:15:54.400
PHIL KESLIN: Thanks
Jamil, and good morning.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:58.187
I'm Phil Keslin, I'm
the CTO for Niantic.

00:15:58.187 --> 00:15:59.770
Most people don't
know, or-- everybody

00:15:59.770 --> 00:16:01.870
knows that we're the
"Pokemon Go" people.

00:16:01.870 --> 00:16:04.660
But what most people don't
know is that we actually

00:16:04.660 --> 00:16:07.360
started inside Google
about six years ago

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:11.500
as an independent organization
with a mission of creating

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:15.010
adventures on foot with others.

00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:17.470
That mission was
set out to foster

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:21.490
exploration and discovery
in the real world.

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:24.270
The first app we launched
is called Field Trip.

00:16:24.270 --> 00:16:27.430
It's a serendipitous
location-based discovery

00:16:27.430 --> 00:16:28.630
application.

00:16:28.630 --> 00:16:30.280
The idea was to
give you information

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:33.070
about the location that
you're currently standing in,

00:16:33.070 --> 00:16:35.200
such as in the
financial district,

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:38.530
most people don't know that
buried beneath the buildings

00:16:38.530 --> 00:16:47.070
are hundreds of ships that
were dragged into the landfill.

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:53.060
That title was launched in
2012, and we followed closely

00:16:53.060 --> 00:16:58.330
with "Ingress," which is
our true location-based MMO.

00:16:58.330 --> 00:17:02.496
It's a territory capture
game and in the four years

00:17:02.496 --> 00:17:04.079
since its launch,
it's been downloaded

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:05.700
about 20 million times.

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:07.650
And it's still
going strong today.

00:17:07.650 --> 00:17:09.785
Its user base is quite sticky.

00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:15.780
Most of you may remember
in an April Fool's joke

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:23.130
at Google in 2014, the Google
Maps was littered with Pokemon.

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:26.250
And the success of
that April Fool's joke

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:28.109
sort of spawned an idea.

00:17:28.109 --> 00:17:31.260
And that idea was,
build a real world

00:17:31.260 --> 00:17:34.410
location-based MMO
based on Pokemon.

00:17:34.410 --> 00:17:37.740
We approached the Pokemon
Company with that idea.

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:39.570
They in turn, played
"Ingress" a little bit

00:17:39.570 --> 00:17:41.130
and discovered
that this actually

00:17:41.130 --> 00:17:43.530
has a great deal of legs to it.

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:45.720
So together with
the Pokemon company,

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:50.040
we built and launched
the "Pokemon Go" game.

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:51.889
We started with a small
team of engineers.

00:17:51.889 --> 00:17:53.430
There were nine
engineers on the team

00:17:53.430 --> 00:17:58.519
that built that product, five
designers and two producers.

00:17:58.519 --> 00:18:00.810
And as many of you are aware,
we were just a little bit

00:18:00.810 --> 00:18:03.540
overwhelmed with the response.

00:18:03.540 --> 00:18:08.100
It was about 50 times what
we originally anticipated.

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:10.420
And yeah, that summer
was quite a wild ride.

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:14.070
Actually, the 30 days,
with absolutely no pressure

00:18:14.070 --> 00:18:17.490
at all except for
maybe the 9,000 people

00:18:17.490 --> 00:18:20.910
in San Francisco who proposed
marching on our offices

00:18:20.910 --> 00:18:23.340
if we couldn't get the servers
back up before the Market

00:18:23.340 --> 00:18:27.390
Street crawl the Friday after we
launched in the United States.

00:18:27.390 --> 00:18:30.199
Since we've launched, we've
stabilized everything.

00:18:30.199 --> 00:18:31.740
We've added some
incremental changes.

00:18:31.740 --> 00:18:34.727
But last week, we launched
the biggest update thus far.

00:18:34.727 --> 00:18:35.810
And let's watch the video.

00:18:35.810 --> 00:18:37.307
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:18:37.307 --> 00:18:40.800
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:15.730 --> 00:19:17.075
[END PLAYBACK]

00:19:17.075 --> 00:19:18.450
PHIL KESLIN: So
with this update,

00:19:18.450 --> 00:19:21.090
we've added the second
generation of Pokemon,

00:19:21.090 --> 00:19:24.330
those Pokemon from the "Gold"
and "Silver" series games.

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:26.610
Additionally, we changed
the counter-mechanics,

00:19:26.610 --> 00:19:29.220
making capturing Pokemon
a bit more challenging.

00:19:29.220 --> 00:19:32.160
And we've added avatar
customization to the title

00:19:32.160 --> 00:19:33.360
as well.

00:19:33.360 --> 00:19:35.820
Since we've launched,
we've had a little

00:19:35.820 --> 00:19:39.600
over 650 million installs
of the application.

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:41.880
And our players are active too.

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:45.700
They've walked about
8.7 billion kilometers,

00:19:45.700 --> 00:19:47.390
which is just shy of Pluto.

00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:53.020
"Ingress" and "Pokemon
Go," as you might imagine,

00:19:53.020 --> 00:19:55.990
they have some pretty
distinct technical challenges.

00:19:55.990 --> 00:19:58.080
This is a single world MMO.

00:19:58.080 --> 00:19:59.505
We're building a
planet-scale game

00:19:59.505 --> 00:20:02.340
with demanding latency and
consistency requirements.

00:20:02.340 --> 00:20:05.970
And it's capable of supporting
millions of simultaneous users,

00:20:05.970 --> 00:20:07.920
and that is no easy task.

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:11.850
Luckily, we've had the support
of both the Google Cloud

00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:14.190
and Google Play Store teams.

00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:17.160
And having those 40 or so
faces during the launch

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:20.100
on the other side of the Hangout
was very, very reassuring

00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:24.780
to the four engineers that were
trying to bring that server up.

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:26.180
When we started
Nianic, we wanted

00:20:26.180 --> 00:20:30.510
to get people outside, off the
couch, playing games with one

00:20:30.510 --> 00:20:31.527
another.

00:20:31.527 --> 00:20:33.360
With "Ingress," and
especially "Pokemon Go,"

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:36.050
we saw this happen.

00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:38.954
Of all that we achieved last
year, it was the smiles.

00:20:38.954 --> 00:20:40.870
And the thing that put
the smiles on our faces

00:20:40.870 --> 00:20:43.630
were the people getting outside,
seeing the teenagers running

00:20:43.630 --> 00:20:47.380
around the neighborhood,
playing games with one another.

00:20:47.380 --> 00:20:51.700
And that is what motivated us
to push through the tough times

00:20:51.700 --> 00:20:56.290
and get a pretty fun
game into people's hands.

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:02.470
Both "Ingress" and "Pokemon
Go," they're not static titles.

00:21:02.470 --> 00:21:04.946
We're going to continue
to evolve those over time.

00:21:04.946 --> 00:21:06.820
And at launch, our game
play for "Pokemon Go"

00:21:06.820 --> 00:21:10.300
was focused on the adventures
on foot part of our mission.

00:21:10.300 --> 00:21:13.240
This year, we're going to
add more and more of the

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:16.450
with others portion of that by
adding social and collaborative

00:21:16.450 --> 00:21:18.464
gameplay to the title as well.

00:21:18.464 --> 00:21:20.380
And we at Niantic look
forward to sharing that

00:21:20.380 --> 00:21:23.800
with you, along with maybe
one or two other surprises.

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:24.588
Thank you.

00:21:24.588 --> 00:21:28.492
