As commander, you'll
partner with Optimus Prime

00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:07.290
to establish a
base and defend it

00:23:07.290 --> 00:23:09.730
with a collection of your
favorite Transformers.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:12.157
So let's dig into that
part of the game right now.

00:23:12.157 --> 00:23:13.528
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:23:13.528 --> 00:23:14.499
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:23:14.499 --> 00:23:16.540
MIKE MCCARTNEY: So last
night while I was asleep,

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:19.110
my friend overseas
raided my base.

00:23:19.110 --> 00:23:22.260
And I found out when I woke up,
and I was really aggravated,

00:23:22.260 --> 00:23:25.470
and all I could think about
was exacting some revenge.

00:23:25.470 --> 00:23:27.450
So why don't we go
and finish off the job

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:29.160
and take out his
boss and his beast?

00:23:34.236 --> 00:23:35.610
JEFF HOWELL: So
for Transformers,

00:23:35.610 --> 00:23:38.280
it was really important for
us that we push the limits

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:40.050
on visuals and really
change people's

00:23:40.050 --> 00:23:43.230
expectations of what is
possible on a mobile platform.

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:46.350
To accomplish this feat, we had
to build a brand new rendering

00:23:46.350 --> 00:23:48.880
engine from the ground
up we'd call Ember.

00:23:48.880 --> 00:23:51.780
Ember combines
physically-based rendering

00:23:51.780 --> 00:23:55.630
and a deferred lighting model
to do a full dynamically lit

00:23:55.630 --> 00:23:59.090
environment, and really
brings our robots to life.

00:23:59.090 --> 00:24:01.920
Devices like the Google
Pixel, like Mike is playing on

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:05.150
right now, have an incredible
amount of rendering horsepower.

00:24:05.150 --> 00:24:06.690
And Ember can extract
all that power

00:24:06.690 --> 00:24:10.260
to bring this console quality
level of graphics to mobile.

00:24:10.260 --> 00:24:12.870
On top of just rendering,
we developed a brand new

00:24:12.870 --> 00:24:15.450
GPU-based physics engine.

00:24:15.450 --> 00:24:18.040
By using multiple
rendered targets

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:22.500
and keeping the physics
state in texture format,

00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:25.680
we can calculate and simulate
collisions for over 50,000

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:29.940
particles, all in real time,
all rendered in beautiful HDR.

00:24:29.940 --> 00:24:33.330
And we even can draw them
all in a single draw call.

